We have done everything humanly possible to save all 9 of these parvo babies. Feeding tubes, albumin transfers, plasma transfers, EVERYTHING. We never declined any treatment and were extremely desperate to save every single one of them. We had already come so far and these babies overcame a lot up until the parvo took over.

Unfortunately we lost two of our smaller puppies 2 days apart. It was absolutely heartbreaking, but they fought as long as they could. One of them passed in Haley’s arms. Both will be privately cremated and buried together.🥺
.
Days after discovering the puppies had parvo my wife became very Ill and had to go to the ER, where she was diagnosed with a parasite she caught from the puppies. We are not including the crazy bill we received from the human hospital in our donations goal, but wanted to share this entire journey with you guys. It’s been ROUGH to say the least. But as you can see we went through way too much to give up on these babies now! 

We are currently over 53k just with hospitalization bills alone and that’s not including ALL the care, medicine, vaccines, supplies we provided over the past 3.5 weeks leading up to the parvo

What we know:

1) We are seeing patches of increases in respiratory cases in the US
2) Many of these dogs are showing mild signs with a few having more severe signs such as pneumonia and needing extra hospitalization and care
3) It is undetermined if this is a new pathogen or if it is one that has historically caused respiratory illness
4) The changes last few years with dogs being less social could be a reason we are seeing increases now in respiratory cases as their immune systems haven’t been challenged with common agents of the respiratory disease umbrella 

Take precautions but don’t panic. I always recommend to keep your dog up to date on vaccines and to keep them away from breeding grounds like dog parks if you can avoid it. If your dog has any ailments take extra precaution with them hanging around lots of unknown dogs or dogs showing any signs of respiratory illness.
